# Setting up the auto-update sync — beginner walkthrough

This guide walks through every step. No prior experience needed.

> **What this does:** Once set up, the case tracker on your Resource Center
> will refresh itself once a day with the latest docket info from
> CourtListener. No manual updates required.

---

## Step 1 — Create a GitHub account

GitHub is a free service that stores code and runs automated tasks.

1. Go to **https://github.com/signup**
2. Enter your email, choose a password, pick a username
3. Verify your email (they'll send a code)
4. On the plan page, pick **Free** — that's all you need

You now have a GitHub account.

---

## Step 2 — Create a new repository (a place to store the project)

1. Once signed in, click the **+** icon in the top-right corner of GitHub
2. Click **New repository**
3. Fill in:
   - **Repository name:** `ialdf-resource-center` (or any name you like)
   - **Description:** optional, e.g. "IALDF Resource Center"
   - Pick **Public** (so the page can be hosted for free) — or Private if you'd rather pay for Private hosting
   - **Leave all checkboxes unchecked** for now (don't add a README, .gitignore, or license)
4. Click **Create repository**

You'll land on a mostly-empty page that says "Quick setup". Keep that tab open.

---

## Step 3 — Upload the project files

You have two options. **Option 3A is easier if you've never used Git.**

### Option 3A — Upload through the website (drag and drop)

1. On the empty repo page, look for the link **"uploading an existing file"** (it's in the middle of the page).
2. Click it. You'll see an upload page.
3. **Open the project folder on your computer.** This is the folder that contains `Resource Center.html`, the `assets/` folder, the `data/` folder, the `.github/` folder, etc.
4. **Select everything inside that folder** (not the folder itself — its contents). On Mac: Cmd-A. On Windows: Ctrl-A.
5. **Drag the selected files onto the GitHub upload area.** GitHub will queue them all.
   - ⚠️ If you don't see the `.github` folder, your computer is hiding dot-folders. On Mac, press Cmd-Shift-. in Finder to show them. On Windows: View menu → Hidden items.
6. Scroll down. In the "Commit changes" box, leave the default message.
7. Click **Commit changes**. Wait — uploading takes a minute.

Skip to Step 4 once the files appear in your repo.

### Option 3B — Use GitHub Desktop (a free app)

If you'll be editing the site often, this is worth setting up:

1. Download **GitHub Desktop** from https://desktop.github.com and install it.
2. Open it and sign in with your GitHub account.
3. **File → Clone repository → URL tab.** Paste your repo URL (e.g. `https://github.com/yourusername/ialdf-resource-center`) and pick a local folder.
4. Copy all the project files into the local folder GitHub Desktop just created.
5. Back in GitHub Desktop, you'll see all the files listed as changes.
6. At the bottom-left, type a commit message like "Initial upload" and click **Commit to main**.
7. Click **Push origin** at the top.

---

## Step 4 — Get your CourtListener API token

1. Go to **https://www.courtlistener.com/sign-up/** and create a free account (or sign in if you have one).
2. Confirm your email.
3. Click your username in the top-right → **Profile**.
4. Click the **API** tab (or visit https://www.courtlistener.com/help/api/rest/).
5. You'll see a long string labeled **API Token**. **Copy it.** Keep it somewhere safe — you'll paste it in the next step.

---

## Step 5 — Tell GitHub your CourtListener token (as a secret)

This stores the token securely so the daily job can use it without exposing it publicly.

1. Go back to your GitHub repo page.
2. Click **Settings** (in the top tab bar of the repo).
3. In the left sidebar: **Secrets and variables → Actions**.
4. Click the green **New repository secret** button.
5. Fill in:
   - **Name:** `COURTLISTENER_TOKEN` (exactly this, all caps, with underscore)
   - **Secret:** paste the token you copied in Step 4
6. Click **Add secret**.

---

## Step 6 — Run the sync for the first time

1. Click the **Actions** tab at the top of your repo.
2. The first time, GitHub may ask you to enable workflows. Click **I understand my workflows, go ahead and enable them** if you see it.
3. In the left sidebar, click **Sync CourtListener**.
4. Above the list of runs, click the **Run workflow** dropdown → **Run workflow** (green button).
5. Wait about 30–60 seconds, then refresh the page. You should see a green checkmark.
6. Click into the run to confirm it succeeded. If anything failed, the logs will tell you why (most common reason: the secret name was misspelled).

After this, the workflow runs by itself every day at 06:00 UTC (about 1–2 AM Eastern). You don't have to do anything.

---

## Step 7 — Put the website online (free hosting)

GitHub can host static sites for free at `https://yourusername.github.io/your-repo-name/`. To turn it on:

1. In your repo, click **Settings → Pages** (in the left sidebar).
2. Under **Source**, pick **Deploy from a branch**.
3. Under **Branch**, pick **main** and **/ (root)**.
4. Click **Save**.
5. Wait a minute. Reload the Pages settings — it'll show you the public URL at the top.
6. Visit that URL and append `/Resource Center.html` to see the site. (If you'd rather, rename the file to `index.html` on your computer, re-upload, and it'll load at the bare URL.)

That's it. The Resource Center is live, and it auto-updates the case tracker every day.

---

## How to add a new case to the tracker

1. In your GitHub repo, click on the `data/` folder, then `dockets.json`.
2. Click the pencil icon (top-right) to edit.
3. Add a new entry following the same format as the others — at minimum: id, name, court, docket_number, status, stage, category, filingDate. Example:
   ```json
   {
     "id": 46,
     "name": "Case name v. Edlow",
     "court": "cand",
     "docket_number": "5:26-cv-99999",
     "status": "PENDING",
     "stage": "Recently filed",
     "category": "Multiple",
     "filingDate": "May 13, 2026"
   }
   ```
4. Scroll down, write a short commit message like "Add Case Name to tracker", and click **Commit changes**.
5. The next scheduled run (or a manual "Run workflow") will pick it up.

CourtListener court codes (a few common ones): `cand` = N.D. California, `mad` = D. Mass., `flsd` = S.D. Florida, `mied` = E.D. Michigan, `dcd` = D.D.C. Full list at https://www.courtlistener.com/api/jurisdictions/.

---

## Troubleshooting

**The Action failed.** Click into the failed run → expand the failing step → read the error.
- "401 Unauthorized" → your token is wrong or not set. Re-do Step 5.
- "secret not found" → the secret name must be exactly `COURTLISTENER_TOKEN`. Re-do Step 5.
- Any other error → screenshot the log and ask for help.

**The page isn't updating.** Open the deployed page in your browser, then open the developer console (F12 → Network tab) and refresh. Look for the request to `data/case-updates.json` — if it's 404, you haven't uploaded the file. If it's 200 but stale, GitHub Pages caches aggressively; wait an hour or hard-refresh with Ctrl-Shift-R / Cmd-Shift-R.

**I want to change the cron schedule.** Edit `.github/workflows/sync.yml` and change the `cron: '0 6 * * *'` line. The format is `minute hour day month weekday` in UTC. Examples:
- Every 6 hours: `0 */6 * * *`
- Once a week (Mondays at noon UTC): `0 12 * * 1`
